In Week 9 of Trump\'92s second term, the pattern that had been forming since January came into sharp relief. The presidency no longer merely leaned on the edges of its authority; it stepped over them and watched to see who would object, and what those objections were worth in practice. Courts issued orders and injunctions. State attorneys general filed suits. University presidents and civil servants tried to hold their ground. Yet the center of gravity moved toward an executive that treated law as a tool, not a boundary, and treated institutions as clay to be reshaped rather than partners to be consulted. This was a week in which the republic\'92s moral floor\'97its shared sense of restraint, truthfulness, and stewardship\'97cracked in several places at once. It did not break, but it bent.\
\
At the close of the prior period, the Democracy Clock stood at 7:44 p.m. It now reads 7:48 p.m., a movement of 3.7 minutes toward night. The shift is modest in appearance, but it reflects a dense cluster of structural changes. The clock moved because executive power was exercised without effective oversight, because law was openly repurposed as a weapon, because the civil service and key agencies were bent toward partisan and private ends, and because whole classes of people\'97migrants, students, dissenters\'97found that their rights depended less on law than on their place in the new order. Courts and civil society did not stand idle; they won injunctions and forced explanations. But the week\'92s story is that of an administration testing whether those wins still bind it, and discovering how much room remains to ignore them.\
\
The clearest line through the week runs from the invocation of the Alien Enemies Act to the deportation flights that took off in defiance of federal court orders. On paper, the president used an eighteenth\uc0\u8209 century wartime statute to target alleged members of a Venezuelan gang, Tren de Aragua. In practice, the order authorized arrests and deportations of noncitizens without the usual due process, in a country not at war with Venezuela. Judge James Boasberg and other federal judges moved quickly, issuing temporary restraining orders and ruling that the act applies only to citizens of enemy nations. They ordered flights halted and, in Boasberg\'92s case, even directed that planes already in the air be turned back. Yet the administration pressed ahead. Planes landed in El Salvador. Deportees were delivered to a \'93terrorism confinement\'94 prison that the United States helped pay to fill. When pressed, the Justice Department argued that the judge\'92s authority stopped at the edge of US airspace, and that verbal instructions not mirrored in written orders could be ignored. In this telling, law was not a limit but a script to be parsed for loopholes.\
\
The people on those flights were not the faceless threats described in presidential proclamations. Affidavits and reporting showed that many had no criminal records. Tattoos\'97crowns, religious symbols, designs with local meaning\'97were treated as proof of gang membership, even as experts noted that Tren de Aragua has no fixed set of marks. A Venezuelan makeup artist and hairdresser, an LGBTQ+ asylum seeker, was deported to a maximum\uc0\u8209 security prison on the strength of such assumptions. Families set up WhatsApp helplines to track loved ones who had vanished into Salvadoran custody. ICE officials insisted that deportees had been \'93carefully vetted,\'94 while at the same time acknowledging that lack of a criminal record did not count in their favor. In this system, innocence was not a shield; it was an irrelevance.\
\
The defiance of court orders did not end at the tarmac. When Judge Boasberg demanded to know why his injunction had been ignored, the Justice Department sought to have him removed from the case, arguing that his orders lacked force once planes left US soil. The administration\'92s filings adopted a tone the judge later described as disrespectful. The president went further, calling Boasberg a \'93Radical Left Lunatic\'94 and demanding his impeachment. A Republican congressman from Texas obliged, filing articles of impeachment that treated a legal ruling as a political offense. Chief Justice John Roberts, in a rare public statement, reminded the country that impeachment is not a remedy for disagreement with judicial decisions. His words defended the principle of judicial independence, but they did not turn the planes around. The clash laid bare how much depends on voluntary compliance.\
\
The same pattern\'97law as weapon, not limit\'97appeared in other domains. On social media and in formal statements, Trump declared that pardons issued by Joe Biden were \'93void, vacant, and of no further force or effect\'94 because they had been signed by autopen. The National Archives quietly explained that the Federal Register uses a standardized graphic of the president\'92s signature, and that autopen\uc0\u8209 signed documents have long been accepted as valid. The point of the declaration was not legal accuracy. It was to signal that protections granted to political opponents, including members of the January 6 committee, could be stripped away at will. In a similar vein, the president signed an order targeting Perkins Coie, a law firm associated with Democratic clients, and continued to attack other firms even after a judge blocked that order. The message to the legal profession was plain: representation of the wrong clients could draw the state\'92s ire.\
