At the same time, the administration moved to change the terrain on which law operates by reshaping the institutions that carry it out. The Department of Government Efficiency\'97DOGE\'97continued to act as the sharp end of this effort. An executive order granted DOGE broad access to unclassified records, data, and software systems across the federal government, in the name of eliminating \'93information silos\'94 and rooting out waste. DOGE teams arrived at the Institute of Museum and Library Services, sent staff home, swore in a new acting director, and canceled contracts and grants, following an order to eliminate the agency. They broke into the US Institute of Peace building over the protests of its leaders, who insisted that it was an independent, congressionally funded nonprofit, not an executive branch office. In each case, DOGE behaved less like an internal auditor and more like a political vanguard, asserting control first and leaving questions of statutory authority for later. That sequence mattered.\
