Courts again pushed back. Judge Ellen Lipton Hollander blocked DOGE from accessing Social Security data, calling its efforts a \'93fishing expedition,\'94 and ordered the destruction of any personal information already obtained. Judge Theodore Chuang ruled that the attempted dismantling of USAID likely violated the Constitution by depriving Congress of its authority over agencies it had created, and ordered parts of the aid agency restored. Yet even these rulings underscored the imbalance of power. They came after staff had been sent home, systems shut down, and programs paused. The law could slow the demolition; it could not prevent the damage already done. The pattern was one of fait accompli, followed by partial repair.\
