The civil service itself was reshaped in ways that blurred the line between public duty and private interest. At the Federal Trade Commission, Trump fired both Democratic commissioners, leaving the agency without a quorum and, in the view of legal analysts, likely violating statutes that protect independent commissioners from at\uc0\u8209 will removal. Without a quorum, the FTC could not bring new enforcement actions against corporate lawbreakers. At the Environmental Protection Agency, leaders announced plans to roll back or eliminate thirty\u8209 one pollution regulations and to gut the Office of Research and Development, potentially firing over a thousand scientists. At the Social Security Administration, internal memos proposed new identity\u8209 proofing rules that would force tens of thousands of elderly and disabled claimants into already overburdened field offices, while a secret freeze on the Enumeration Beyond Entry program threatened to send 60,000 to 75,000 new workers and citizens a week into the same lines just to obtain Social Security numbers. In each case, the stated aim was efficiency or integrity. The practical effect was to make it harder for ordinary people to claim benefits and protections, and easier for the executive to steer agencies without resistance from expert staff.\
