Into this weakened administrative landscape stepped private actors with close ties to the president. Elon Musk\'92s Starlink network was installed across the White House campus as a \'93donation,\'94 approved by the Secret Service but not subjected to the usual procurement process. The same week, senators called for investigations into the Federal Aviation Administration\'92s decision to cancel a $2.4 billion contract with Verizon and instead pay Starlink to manage US airspace. Musk was scheduled to receive a Pentagon briefing on war plans for a potential conflict with China, a plan later walked back after public reporting and concern over his business ties to that country. Trump himself acknowledged that Musk\'92s interests in China made him an unsuitable recipient of such plans, even as Musk\'92s companies deepened their role in US military launches and communications. The boundary between contractor and policymaker, between private oligarch and public steward, grew thinner. It was not just influence; it was integration.\
