Law enforcement rhetoric followed suit. The Attorney General charged three people accused of setting fire to Tesla vehicles and charging stations with \'93violent destruction of Tesla properties\'94 and framed the acts as domestic terrorism. Trump suggested that those who vandalized Tesla cars should face twenty\uc0\u8209 year sentences in El Salvador\'92s prisons. Steve Bannon defended the mass deportations to that same prison system, acknowledging that \'93innocent gardeners\'94 might be swept up but calling it a \'93tough break.\'94 MAGA supporters made bomb threats against judges who had ruled against the administration, including Justice Amy Coney Barrett. In this climate, dissent was not merely criticized; it was recast as a security threat, and those who enforced legal limits on executive power were treated as enemies. The line between protest and \'93terrorism\'94 grew easier to move.\
