Civil society, too, adapted. Democratic attorneys general held community impact hearings across the country, gathering testimony from veterans, immigrants, and federal workers about the effects of Trump\'92s policies. Their aim was both legal and narrative: to build a record that could support lawsuits and to give voice to those whose lives were being reordered from above. Women\'92s groups launched campaigns to extradite figures accused of gender\uc0\u8209 based violence. Representative Jasmine Crockett helped organize a nationwide, nonviolent protest at Tesla dealerships, urging people to sell their cars and stock as a form of economic pressure. These efforts did not stop the week\'92s executive orders or deportation flights. But they showed that the space for organized resistance, though narrowed, had not yet closed.\
