By the end of Week 9, the Democracy Clock\'92s new time\'977:48 p.m.\'97captured more than a sum of discrete events. It marked a week in which the executive branch claimed supremacy over the judiciary in practice, if not yet in doctrine; in which agencies designed to serve the public were repurposed to serve a narrow coalition of political and economic allies; and in which the rights and status of hundreds of thousands of people were made contingent on their nationality, ideology, or place in the cultural wars. The civic covenant, as the moral floor analysis suggests, did not shatter outright. Courts still issued orders. Journalists still reported. Protesters still organized. But the covenant did crack. Restraint gave way to emergency\uc0\u8209 style governance. Truthfulness yielded to curated narratives and strategic erasure. Stewardship of public goods and institutions was traded for short\u8209 term advantage and private gain.\
