The significance of this week lies not only in what changed, but in what was normalized. Deportation flights that ignored court orders. Executive orders that treated congressionally created departments as disposable. A private billionaire woven into the fabric of national security planning. Universities told that their funding depends on whom they discipline and whom they admit. Once such practices are established, they are hard to unwind. That is why the clock moved. It records not the noise of politics, but the quiet shift in what the system can be counted on to prevent. At 7:48 p.m., there is still light in the sky. Institutions still function. Opposition still speaks. But the distance to night has shortened, and the path back to a safer hour has grown steeper.\
